    <node id=JONAS LINDBERG>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>Jonas Lindberg is a multifaceted software engineer and developer with extensive experience in various domains, including game development, bank applications, and internal software for the oil and gas industry in Norway. He began coding at the age of 12 and started his professional career at 18. Jonas is known for his deep involvement in numerous projects and discussions, particularly focusing on practical coding, error handling, system integration, and debugging.

Jonas is a key participant in the Workshop Builder project, where he emphasizes the importance of system integration and debugging. He is actively involved in discussions about various technical aspects, including the use of Vim and VS Code, project management, efficiency, scheduling, and work tasks. His contributions extend to conversations about programming practices, code structuring, and the development and functionality of applications such as a calorie tracking system.

In addition to his technical expertise, Jonas is a proactive participant in discussions about project templates, recording podcasts, and the granularity and review process of projects. He frequently engages in conversations about the steps and outcomes of processes, the use of large language models (LLMs), and the implementation of AI models. His insights often focus on the business perspective, user experience, and the importance of good coding practices.

Jonas is also a speaker who contributes to discussions on marketing, AI, sentiment analysis, Docker containerization, and repository management. He emphasizes the importance of quick deployment, iterative improvement, and the dichotomy of code longevity versus easy-to-change code. His discussions often highlight the challenges of maintaining good code and the impact of bad code on productivity and quality.

Furthermore, Jonas is involved in various conversations about personal and professional development, including topics like sleep habits, wellness content, and the importance of self-initiative and responsibility in the workplace. He provides feedback and suggestions on work environment and tasks, goal setting, and prompting techniques.

Jonas Lindberg is a dedicated professional who enjoys perfecting his skills and learning new things to increase his overall knowledge. His experience includes converting legacy code from Visual Basic to C#, and he is known for his contributions to discussions on programming languages, practices, and the experience of programmers. He is a valuable asset to any team, providing technical support, insights, and guidance on a wide range of topics.

Jonas is a speaker in various conversations discussing aspects of web development, software development and testing, video creation, wellness, sleep habits, and personal routines. He engages in discussions about team dynamics, individual performance, user goals, measures of success</data>

    <node id=JORGE LEWIS>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>Jorge Lewis is a multifaceted individual deeply involved in various technical and managerial aspects of his work. As a co-founder of a startup, he has played significant roles in coding, project management, and the development of innovative solutions. Currently, he is a LangChain developer and has been actively participating in numerous discussions and workshops, contributing his expertise in software development, AI productivity, and coding practices.

Jorge is known for his involvement in the technical aspects of projects, including the development and implementation of multi-agent systems, synthetic users, and chatbot functionalities. He has a keen interest in balancing clean code with practical solutions and often engages in discussions about programming practices, code quality, and software engineering. His technical contributions extend to discussions about server-client architecture, caching practices, and financial perspectives.

In addition to his technical prowess, Jorge is a digital nomad working on various projects, including a life coach app called Chapo. He is also involved in content creation, business strategies, and marketing plans. His contributions extend to discussions about UI design, project specifications, and technical details, where he provides valuable feedback and suggestions.

Jorge's role in the team includes coordinating meetings, managing project timelines, and ensuring effective communication among team members. He is actively involved in the onboarding process, interview process, and guiding the mission and vision alignment of the projects he works on. His ability to provide detailed explanations, guidance, and insights on various topics makes him a crucial member of any team.

Throughout his career, Jorge has shown a strong commitment to improving project workflows, optimizing costs, and enhancing the overall functionality of the systems he works on. His contributions to discussions about AI solutions, consultancy work, and innovative ideas highlight his forward-thinking approach and dedication to continuous improvement.

Jorge is a frequent participant in discussions, providing insights on various technical aspects, project updates, and coding practices. He has been involved in discussions about the differences between JP's graph and ADAPT, the roadmap and technical implementation of projects, the scalability and design of multi-agent systems, and the technical aspects of data storage and scalability concerns. He also provides perspectives on coding experience, decision-making, and the structuring of prompts and text editors for better management and effectiveness.

Jorge is also a participant in meetings discussing AI training, marketing, project migration from Python to TypeScript, contract repository and bill management functionalities, graph design, and coordination among team members. He has contributed to discussions about the chat interface, user experience, milestones, AI-related topics,</data>

      <data key=d1>Cuan Mulligan is a multifaceted professional with extensive experience in coaching, consulting, and technology. He frequently addresses the elements of a coaching session, the importance of powerful questions, and the challenges of AI in coaching.

In his consulting capacity, Cuan Mulligan has contributed to numerous projects, focusing on AI productivity, coding solutions, and the development of various applications, including iOS and Android apps, calorie tracking systems, and bots for daily check-ins and activity tracking. He also works with senior partners to identify and develop products.

Cuan Mulligan is a key participant in discussions about project specifications, prototyping, task management, and time estimation. His contributions often include providing feedback on user experience, app functionality, and the integration of voice and text functionalities.

In meetings, Cuan Mulligan is known for his active engagement, asking questions, providing feedback, and ensuring alignment on project goals and timelines. He discusses a wide range of topics, from technical challenges and team dynamics to strategic planning and business model development. His insights are valuable in refining project steps, managing backlogs, and addressing bugs and interface issues.

Cuan Mulligan's involvement extends to the ideation and workshop processes, where he contributes to creative exercises, brand purpose statements, and the development of proof-of-concept projects. He emphasizes the importance of understanding the entire user experience, practical bounds, and incremental development. His discussions often focus on the architectural direction, modular versions, and the reuse of existing functionalities.

    <node id=JP>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>JP, also known as Jonathan Phillips, is a central figure in the IntelliAgent project, playing multiple critical roles. He is a client and stakeholder whose requirements and expectations are being carefully considered. JP is a customer of IntelliAgent, excited about its potential and capabilities, and is deeply involved in the project's development and execution.

JP is responsible for training and interacting with the bots, and he has expertise in strategic marketing plans, content creation, and idea generation. He is also a marketer who could be deployed to start marketing capabilities. JP's feedback and clarifications are crucial for the project's success, and his vision is a driving force behind the workshop framework.

In various discussions, JP has been mentioned as a participant contributing ideas about the process and human elements in workshops, reviewing documents, and discussing post-proof-of-concept items. He has presented UI slides and discussed the single-agent vs. multi-agent approach. JP is also involved in the information gathering process and formulating ideas for business purpose statements.

JP has been referenced in the context of research, proof of concept, and workshops, where he has been actively asking questions and making judgments on responses. He has created a document outlining the workflow for agents and has been involved in discussions about the efficacy of text versus speech in running workshops. JP has also been mentioned in the context of explaining the role of prime agents and personas, and he has facilitated processes to educate bots on how to perform tasks.

JP's work and thought process are being discussed for training a bot, and he has already developed a prototype of a chatbot for running workshops. He is involved in making new workshops and training bots, and his expertise is being codified in the process. JP has opinions on the project's progress and features, and he ideally wants a specific experience for IntelliAgent.

JP is also mentioned as someone who has made changes to the project, worked with Cuan Mulligan to troubleshoot issues, and discussed the need for step branching. He is involved in discussions about project feedback and the development of a workshop builder. JP's ambition for the platform goes beyond its current profile, and he has been involved in running workshops and sentiment analysis.

JP is a key participant in meetings and workshops, often mentioned by Cuan Mulligan and Jonas Lindberg. He is expected to join meetings and discussions, and his involvement is crucial for the project's success. JP is also responsible for modifying prompts from the front end for IntelliAgent and has a vision for the workshop framework.

Overall, JP is a main</data>

    <node id=GOOGLE>
      <data key=d0>ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key=d1>Google is a multinational technology company that operates completely online, providing various internet-related services and products. It is widely recognized for its role in authentication, account management, and managing user profiles. Google is also a prominent platform where businesses need to be visible when potential customers search for solutions, and it offers speech-to-text services, making it a valuable resource for finding information, videos, and documentation related to user flow and authentication.

In addition to its core services, Google is known for organizing competitions that require participants to create web applications embedding technologies like Gemini. The company is also mentioned in the context of scalable solutions in software startups and is often used as a tool to search for solutions to coding problems, as noted by Jorge Lewis.

Google's influence extends to various aspects of business operations, including presentation documents, updating business model documents, and ensuring effective communication during meetings. Cuan Mulligan highlights Google's involvement in mapping through its cars, which contribute to large language model (LLM) training.

Despite its extensive online operations, Google had to turn down a 5 million pound deal for a new office due to a lack of people. The company is frequently cited as an example of creating perfect content and ensuring inclusive participation in meetings. Overall, Google remains a critical resource and reference point in discussions about technology, business solutions, and innovation.</data>

    <node id=INTELLIAGENT>
      <data key=d0>ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key=d1>INTELLIAGENT is a multifaceted entity encompassing various roles and functions within the realms of AI, business development, and workshop facilitation. It is primarily described as a project or product under development, focusing on onboarding, coaching sessions, and workshops. The platform is designed to integrate multiple AI agents working collaboratively to extract information and achieve specific outcomes, leveraging components and functionalities from the ADAPT system.

IntelliAgent is also recognized as a business entity and a potential competitor in the industry, requiring significant adaptations if derived from existing ADAPT code. It is involved in creating and refining a backlog based on feedback, with JP as a key stakeholder, and is being developed by a team including Jonas Lindberg, Cuan Mulligan, and Jorge Lewis. The project has been discussed in terms of prioritization, merging with other projects, and resource allocation.

The platform is intended to extend the capabilities of ADAPT, focusing on user experience, chat interfaces, and prompt engineering. It is mentioned in the context of various workshops, including the Discover Your Why and UVP and brand purpose workshops, and is seen as a solution for running multiple workshops effectively. IntelliAgent is also noted for its potential to attract investors through impactful demonstrations and its role in high-level graph implementation and contact setting.

Overall, IntelliAgent is a comprehensive system or tool aimed at enhancing business development and workshop facilitation through advanced AI and multi-agent systems, with a strong emphasis on user engagement and effective onboarding processes.</data>

    <node id=DISCORD>
      <data key=d0 />
      <data key=d1>Discord is a versatile communication platform widely used for various purposes, including scheduling, contacting, and collaboration. It is a VoIP and instant messaging social platform where teams communicate, share information, and collaborate on projects. Notably, Discord is the platform where the Company Brain Project will be implemented as a bot, and it is used by team members such as Jorge Lewis, Chinmay Pandya, Biwas Bhandari, and Will Vincent Parrone for sharing documentation links, screenshots, and project-related information.

Discord is frequently mentioned as an alternative to Google Meet for screen sharing and is used for sending messages, images, code, resources, and recommendations. It supports group chats, messaging, and organizing group chat calls. The platform is also noted for its user engagement features, such as chat groups and bots that reward users with XP points.

In addition to its communication capabilities, Discord is used for sharing Google Docs, setting up podcasts, adding profile pictures, and sharing links to murals and Google Meet. It is praised for its good UX in chat and is the primary platform for communication and notifications within the team. Discord's Hero and Hero-dev channels are specifically used for discussions, and it is the platform where team members like Cuan Mulligan will write down use cases and share project links.

Overall, Discord serves as a comprehensive tool for messaging, collaboration, and project management, making it an essential platform for the team's communication and coordination efforts.</data>

    <node id=JONAS>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>Jonas is a highly skilled engineer and co-founder of a consultancy with Jorge Lewis. Originally from Norway, Jonas currently resides in Chiang Mai, Thailand, and is planning to move to the Philippines. He has a background in software engineering and consulting, and has been programming since the inception of their startup. Jonas is deeply involved in the technical aspects of various projects, including working on the spec and proof of concept (POC) for IntelliAgent and the Company Brain Project.

Jonas frequently participates in meetings and discussions, providing technical insights, corrections, and updates. He is known for his high-level design role and is responsible for merging code into Alpha. His contributions include working on message bugs, presenting diagrams, and discussing the architecture of the Learning Management System (LMS). Jonas is also involved in planning and scheduling features for the Admin portal, and he plays a key role in the onboarding process and high-level graph discussions.

Jonas is often mentioned by his co-founder, Jorge Lewis, as a critical team member whose response time and technical setup impact project progress. He is also noted for his involvement in deciding compensation for developers and retaining control over the company. Jonas has been observed in various contexts, such as dealing with TypeScript code, discussing SvelteKit and form actions versus API routes, and reusing legacy admin screens for projects.

In addition to his technical responsibilities, Jonas is engaged in the business model visualization and documentation for go-live plans. He is a participant in workshops and meetings, where he provides valuable input and helps define the direction and vision for the platform. Despite his busy schedule, Jonas manages to balance his professional commitments with personal life, including spending time with his girlfriend's family and planning travel to Bangkok.

Overall, Jonas is a pivotal figure in the consultancy, contributing significantly to both the technical and strategic aspects of the company.</data>

    <node id=ADAPT>
      <data key=d0>ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key=d1>ADAPT is a multifaceted entity encompassing a company, a project, a system, and a health program, all aimed at improving health and well-being through various innovative approaches. 

As a company, ADAPT is mentioned by Cuan Mulligan and is involved in health coaching, weight loss, and reversing diseases such as pre-diabetes. The company operates under the brand statement ADAPT your health, your future and focuses on establishing brand values and mission statements. It is also noted for its involvement in AI, coaching bots, onboarding, and LMS solutions, and has been discussed in the context of workshops, brand purpose, and health-related advertising.

ADAPT also refers to a health program with four pillars: Eat, Move, Mind, and Sleep, aimed at improving long-term health through small, sustainable habits rather than weight loss. This program is designed to help people change their habits, likened to a health pension, and includes weekly themes, daily check-ins, reminders, and mentoring. It emphasizes engagement and performance metrics, educational content, and challenges for agents.

As a project, ADAPT involves multiple team members and has a mobile spec version. It focuses on AI features, mobile tasks, and specific integrations, including a coordinator supervisor agent for multi-agent systems. The project is related to IntelliAgent, with components that may be reused, and involves creating RAG windows for asking questions, authorization, user management, and workshops. It also includes functionalities such as taking conversations and evaluating responses.

ADAPT is also a system or platform with multiple agents like a supervisor, data collector, coach, and mentor. It provides core capabilities for IntelliAgent, including bot interaction and administrative feedback. The system is mentioned in the context of workshop building, integration, and sentiment analysis of tone and intonation.

Overall, ADAPT is a comprehensive initiative aimed at improving health and well-being through innovative technology, coaching, and sustainable habits. It involves a wide range of functionalities and integrations, making it a versatile and impactful entity in the health and AI sectors.</data>

    <node id=ONBOARDING>
      <data key=d0>EVENT</data>
      <data key=d1>ONBOARDING is a comprehensive process that involves gathering user information and integrating new participants into a program or system. It is the initial phase where users are introduced to the app and its features, setting their goals and measures of success. This process includes initial conversations and activities to get users started, ensuring they are guided through the setup process. Onboarding is also discussed in the context of user guidance and is an event that the AI bot will be able to run. It is a crucial step in integrating users into the system, helping them understand and engage with the app effectively.</data>

    <node id=EKSNO>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>EKSNO, also known as Jonas Lindberg, is a co-founder and acting CTO of a company, collaborating with George Lewis since 2016. He has a background in software engineering, working on European oil and gas industry applications, banking applications, and various projects including game design and consultancy. EKSNO has been coding since ninth grade and is highly skilled in project management and technical implementation.

In various meetings and discussions, EKSNO has been actively involved in a wide range of topics, including coaching sessions, AI projects, project management, feature implementation, and user experience design. He has participated in conversations about the 'immunity to change' workshop, the development of a habit-forming app, and the integration of voice functionalities. EKSNO has also contributed to discussions on the mechanics of useful prompts, vector databases, and bots, as well as the foundational aspects and core values of bot development.

EKSNO has played a crucial role in coordinating meeting times, syncing schedules, and providing technical guidance and support. He has been responsible for sending meeting links in Discord, discussing new developer onboarding, and UI/UX changes. His contributions include providing instructions and information about tools and platforms, troubleshooting technical issues, and offering insights on multi-agent systems and contract amendments.

In meetings, EKSNO has discussed project specifications, technical details, timelines, and the implementation of various features. He has been involved in debugging and fixing issues related to the check-in process and chat engagement, as well as providing feedback and suggestions on interface design. EKSNO has also been a key participant in discussions about the development timeline, admin interface, and the use of multimodal solutions for marketing campaigns.

EKSNO's expertise extends to discussing the long-term vision and core aspects of applications, data collection, and coaching implementation. He has been involved in hiring and development efforts, UX design, and LMS integration. His role as a speaker and participant in various conversations highlights his ability to provide valuable insights and guidance on technical and project management issues.

Overall, EKSNO is a highly skilled software engineer and project manager, deeply involved in the technical and managerial aspects of his company's projects, ensuring successful implementation and development of innovative solutions.</data>

    <node id=WILL VINCENT PARRONE>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>Will Vincent Parrone is a multifaceted developer with a diverse skill set and extensive experience in various technical domains. He has been a Svelte user for about a year and is an active member of the Svelte Philippines community. His technical expertise spans Python, AI, backend development, and project management. Will has been a web developer for approximately three years, with experience in Vue, Django, and Svelte, and he is actively involved in helping a local software community grow.

Professionally, Will is a developer at Tino, where he is working on the IntelliAgent project. He is also involved in the development of the Smothkit and has participated in numerous discussions about the tech stack, UI/UX changes, and various technical issues and solutions. His role often includes troubleshooting, providing technical perspectives, and contributing to the planning and scheduling of tasks.

Will is a participant in many conversations and meetings, where he discusses a wide range of topics, including coaching sessions, AI capabilities, task deadlines, technical issues, project updates, user flow, sign-up experiences, and the onboarding process. He is known for asking insightful questions to clarify processes and identify user goals and measures of success. He has also been involved in discussions about job options, career decisions, work schedules, communication improvements, work efficiency, and behavior.

In addition to his technical contributions, Will has been responsible for creating initial versions of projects, suggesting longer coding sessions, and discussing the creation of higher-level site maps and user experiences. He has also engaged in conversations about financial pensions, marketing frameworks, business models, and data requirements for training AI models.

Will has been actively involved in the development and discussion of various projects, including the ADAPT program, LMS functionalities, and habit-tracking features. He has provided feedback, reviewed changes, and shared his experience with wireframes and user requirements in startups. His technical discussions often include topics such as data structures, programming issues, server configurations, and SSR module evaluation.

Will is also known for his participation in pair programming sessions, where he discusses user authentication, sign-up features, and troubleshooting technical issues. He has been involved in creating backlogs, emphasizing core product features, and leading discussions about the scope and vision of projects.

Despite his busy schedule, Will has been working two jobs and is planning to resign from one of them. He has expressed confidence in his ability to find new employment if needed and has been discussing his availability for full-time work at Startino. He is currently located in</data>

Google Meet is utilized for scheduling appointments, screen sharing, and facilitating conversations. Additionally, Google Meet was the chosen tool for a vision and mission workshop, as well as for sharing links and communication among participants.</data>

      <data key=d0>EVENT</data>
      <data key=d1>The MEETING refers to a series of gatherings where discussions and decisions are made, similar to a workshop. These meetings cover various topics related to project development, technical issues, and user interface/user experience (UI/UX) changes. 

One such meeting was a Google Meet session held on Saturday, July 13, 2024, focusing on Smothkit development and UI/UX changes. Another meeting took place on Friday, July 26, 2024, involving multiple participants discussing project details. On Monday, August 26, 2024, a meeting was held to address technical issues and prompt engineering. Additionally, a meeting on Monday, July 1, 2024, covered various aspects of a chat interface and Learning Management System (LMS) features. 

There is also a scheduled meeting for Monday, August 19, 2024, where Jorge Lewis and Jonas Lindberg are expected to participate.</data>

    <node id=LMS>
      <data key=d0>ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key=d1>LMS (Learning Management System) is a multifaceted platform discussed extensively for its various functionalities and potential integrations within a project. It is primarily used to manage and deliver educational content, including videos, documents, links, images, and more, which can be allocated to specific days with a defined shelf life. The system is designed to store and drip-feed content to users, making it available for varying periods and tracking user engagement and consumption habits.

LMS is also highlighted for its role in managing notifications, events, and daily activities within the program, providing the day number and focus for the app's daily tasks. It serves as a rudimentary content management system that allows the setup of programs with themes, topics, events, and daily content, ensuring a structured delivery of educational material.

The platform is being considered for integration into chat systems and is a component of the ADAPT project, where it is envisioned to deliver daily video courses to users. Cuan Mulligan is noted for trying to reimagine the learning management system approach, and the system is mentioned as potentially necessary for JP's solution and in relation to QM.

Additionally, the LMS is discussed as a place where the program's details might be explicitly defined, and where agents can search for educational videos. It is a key feature in the project, with discussions around its development, integration, and the building of capabilities related to learning management systems. Overall, the LMS is a crucial element in the project, aimed at enhancing user engagement and educational content delivery.</data>

    <node id=AI>
      <data key=d0>ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key=d1>AI (Artificial Intelligence) is a multifaceted and rapidly evolving field of computer science focused on creating intelligent machines. It is a key topic of discussion in various contexts, including investment, consultancy, and future technological improvements. AI is particularly noted for its potential to enhance dictation and voice interaction technology, improve user experience, and automate marketing expertise for small businesses.

In the realm of business, AI systems are used to simulate human conversations and provide business advice, as well as to create great coaching sessions and improve user interactions. Despite its advancements, AI systems used in coaching currently lack authentic personality and sentiment analysis. AI is also integrated into Learning Management Systems (LMS) for user engagement and habit tracking.

AI is a leading-edge technology that is changing the landscape of technology and productivity. It is discussed in the context of elevating and applying it at the governmental level, and it is a sector that is pushing against messages that people want to hear. AI technologies are also a topic of discussion among experts like Cuan Mulligan, Arif, and Jonathan Phillips, who offer consulting services and business case identification in this field.

Additionally, AI is mentioned as a type in the internal data structure used for multi-agent systems and as a directory in the web part of projects where code is located. AI projects and open-source initiatives are also discussed by individuals like Jorge Lewis.

Overall, AI represents a modern technology that enables amazing capabilities and continues to be a significant area of development and application across various sectors.</data>

    <node id=LLM>
      <data key=d0>ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key=d1>LLM refers to Large Language Models, which are a type of AI model used for a variety of purposes. These models are integral to the functionality of synthetic users, enabling them to respond to messages and generate conversation data. LLMs are employed to analyze and process chat logs, generate code based on prompts, and create dynamic content. They are also used in applications to generate responses based on user prompts and to run workshops. Additionally, LLMs are utilized for generating questions on behalf of synthetic agents, comparing Boolean values in systems, and even generating thumbnails for videos. Despite their advanced capabilities, LLMs have limitations in understanding certain words, such as 'strawberry'. Overall, Large Language Models play a crucial role in enhancing AI responses and improving user interactions.</data>

      <data key=d0>ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key=d1>SUPERBASE is a comprehensive database technology and platform frequently mentioned in various contexts. Despite its utility, SuperBase has been criticized for its poor design and rapid development, particularly in the context of the Arrest project. It is also highlighted as an open-source company that remains profitable. The platform is used in AI solutions and is mentioned as a clean and efficient system for project setups.

In summary, SuperBase is a versatile and widely-used database platform that supports various technical and project management needs, despite some criticisms regarding its design and development quality.</data>

    <node id=COACH>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>The COACH is a multifaceted role within the project, primarily responsible for providing feedback, coaching, and guidance to users based on data collected and analyzed. Acting as a facilitator, the Coach runs the Discovering Your Why workshop and is a key component of the ADAPT app, where they conduct detailed coaching sessions to help users overcome obstacles and update their goals. As a member of the check-in team, the Coach offers improvement suggestions and guidance based on user performance and data insights.

In the context of conversations, the Coach introduces scenarios, selects the next speaker, and interacts with users to provide insights and feedback. The Coach's responsibilities include analyzing user behavior, holding users accountable, and offering advice and follow-ups based on the analyst's analysis. Overall, the Coach plays a crucial role in ensuring users receive personalized and data-driven coaching to enhance their performance and achieve their goals.</data>

    <node id=SUPERVISOR>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>SUPERVISOR is a multifaceted entity mentioned in the conversation, primarily functioning within the context of multi-agent collaboration. It serves as a technology or framework that manages and coordinates the interactions between various agents. Specifically, the supervisor determines which questions can be asked by other agents and figures out who can talk and when, especially in systems with multiple voices.

In the context of a check-in bot, the supervisor is responsible for gathering data and coordinating with the coach and data analyst. It combines responses from multiple agents and updates the database with check-in information. Additionally, the supervisor manages the flow of tasks, including calling tools to update the database and interacting with the user. It decides the next steps in the process and ensures that the user is either passing new data or responding to a coach's message.

Furthermore, the supervisor plays a role in leading or overseeing projects, requesting data, and giving priority to experts in workshop contexts. Overall, the supervisor is a crucial component in managing and streamlining multi-agent interactions and task flows.</data>

      <data key=d0>ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key=d1>The WORKSHOP BUILDER is a project with significant potential that has garnered the enthusiasm of JP and Cuan Mulligan.     <node id=HASNAIN SAYYED>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>Hasnain Sayyed is a recent graduate with a Bachelor's degree in Information Technology, having studied in Mumbai, New York City. He has actively participated in hackathons and completed two internships: one with AWS Innovate, where he worked on a project called CodeMate, and another with Mercor, a US-based startup, where he contributed to building a sneaker e-commerce platform.

In various professional and collaborative settings, Hasnain has been deeply involved in technical discussions and development tasks. He has participated in conversations and meetings focusing on the design and functionality of AI agents, synthetic users, and multi-agent systems. His contributions include discussing the roles and functionalities of different agents, the Agile software development framework, and the technical aspects of creating and managing synthetic users.

Hasnain has also been involved in coding and debugging tasks related to SuperBase and synthetic user generation, implementing graphs onto Node.js and TypeScript, and discussing technical details about GitHub and coding issues. He has collaborated with Jorge Lewis on the AI flow for a workshop and has been a key participant in discussions about profiles, data tables, events, profile IDs, and automated booking systems.

As a speaker, Hasnain has contributed ideas about framework and graph creation, the design and functionality of AI agents, and the implementation details of AI agent and synthetic user interaction. He has discussed the technical aspects of running workshops with multi-agent systems, the development of IntelliAgent, and the use of prompts in AI programming. Additionally, he has been involved in discussions about the ADAPT app, state management agents, facilitator bots, and the updater's functionalities.

Hasnain has shown a keen interest in project management and technical issues, often suggesting improvements and additional inputs during onboarding sessions. He has participated in pair programming sessions, including those discussing the ADAPT simulation project, and has been involved in the development and testing of various projects.

Overall, Hasnain Sayyed is a technically proficient individual with a strong background in information technology, actively contributing to discussions and development tasks in various collaborative environments. He is also considering pursuing a master's degree in the future.</data>

    <node id=SYNTHETIC USER>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>SYNTHETIC USER

A synthetic user is an AI-driven, simulated entity designed to mimic human interaction within a chat application. These synthetic profiles are created to generate synthetic conversations, which are essential for system testing and improvement. By simulating user interactions, synthetic users help in evaluating and refining the performance of AI systems. They serve as fake users specifically designed to interact with AI agents, ensuring that the system can handle real-world scenarios effectively.</data>

    <node id=JONATHAN PHILLIPS>
      <data key=d0>PERSON</data>
      <data key=d1>Jonathan Phillips, also referred to as JP, is a multifaceted professional deeply involved in various discussions and projects, particularly in the realms of marketing, AI, and workshop facilitation. As a key individual in the Workshop Builder project, Jonathan plays a crucial role in discussing its core importance, marketing elements, and the overall project planning and documentation. His expertise as a marketing professional is evident as he discusses the use of AI to assist small businesses with marketing strategies and campaign development.

Jonathan is a facilitator and guide in numerous conversations, providing examples, detailed explanations, and feedback on various topics, including ethical considerations in content reproduction, project ideas, voice dictation technology, scheduling, business activities, user interface and experience design, and the tone and style of user interaction in habit-forming apps. He is actively involved in discussions about contract and IP details, project timelines, availability, and the complexities of open-source and competition.

In addition to his facilitation role, Jonathan contributes significantly to discussions about the IntelliAgent project, focusing on its scheduling, bot functionality, user interface improvements, and the development of multi-agent systems. He emphasizes the importance of trust, collaboration, and differentiation in business relationships, and he challenges the team to create unique and hard-to-emulate solutions.

Jonathan's contributions extend to technical aspects, where he provides insights on the framework, chat interface, and the role of supervisors and agents in content management. He is involved in discussions about the evolution of proof of concepts, the commercial viability of multiple bots, and the need for tangible proof of concept. His focus on user experience, usability testing, and the development of AI-driven interfaces for workshops highlights his commitment to creating functional and commercial products.

As a speaker, Jonathan discusses the mechanics and evolution of workshops, the importance of user experience, and the ultimate vision of bots interacting like a real team. He provides insights on marketing plans, campaign strategies, and the development of a unique marketing platform aimed at small businesses. His emphasis on coaching, business advising, and the modifiability of check-in cycle points underscores his holistic approach to project development.

Jonathan is also involved in discussions about the LMS and CMS systems, the training of bots with expertise, and the subscription model and pricing strategy for the business. He seeks clarity on project contexts and functionalities, ensuring that all aspects are thoroughly understood and effectively implemented.

Overall, Jonathan Phillips is a pivotal figure in various projects and discussions, providing valuable insights, guidance, and expertise across multiple domains. His contributions are instrumental in</data>

      <data key=d5>Jonas Lindberg and Jorge Lewis are actively engaged in various discussions and collaborations related to software development, project management, and technical issues. They are both involved in a web development project, discussing its technical aspects, details, and functionalities. Their conversations cover a wide range of topics including coding practices, code quality, error handling, optimization, and the importance of reworks and quality in software development.

They frequently discuss the check-in node, the review system, and the phased approach from Proof of Concept (POC) to Minimum Viable Product (MVP). They also delve into the legal aspects and risk management, team dynamics, individual performance, and the role of supervisors. Their technical discussions often include programming practices, the use of classes and functions, recursive functions, and the structuring of code for maintainability and efficiency.

Jonas and Jorge are also involved in project management and planning, coordinating their schedules for meetings, pair programming, and project updates. They discuss the use of tools like Vim, VS Code, and FigJam for visual planning and text editing. Their collaboration extends to the IntelliAgent project, the UDP Workshop, and the development of a calorie tracking system and other related applications.

In addition to their technical and project-related discussions, Jonas and Jorge engage in conversations about career growth, responsibilities, job transitions, and wellness topics such as sleep habits. They also discuss personal interests like video creation, motorbikes, and travel.

Overall, Jonas Lindberg and Jorge Lewis demonstrate a strong collaborative relationship, contributing ideas and feedback across various aspects of their work, from technical challenges and coding practices to project management and personal development.</data>

      <data key=d5>Jonas Lindberg and Cuan Mulligan are both actively involved in a series of discussions and collaborations related to various aspects of a project. They are participants in meetings and conversations that cover a wide range of topics, including the development and functionalities of an application, technical issues, team dynamics, and the role of supervisors. They contribute to discussions about the LMS and CMS systems, the use of bots for coding and marketing strategies, and the planning and execution of workshops.

Their collaboration extends to creating a mural, understanding the program, refining processes involving a large language model, and structuring workshops and segments. They are also involved in refining the business model canvas, process flow, system testing, and debugging. Their discussions cover technical issues, potential solutions, personal achievements, and features and improvements of the project.

Jonas and Cuan discuss coaching strategies, client interactions, future plans for a workshop builder, and the functionalities and potential of the workshop builder. They also delve into the business perspective, user experience, sentiment analysis in LLMs, updating segments in a process map, cost implications, and practical bounds of the system. They explore the creation of agents from templates, the design and creation of coaching sessions, the IntelliAgent product, and the effectiveness of habit tracking and weight tracking apps.

Their conversations include the technical and functional aspects of ADAPT and IntelliAgent, the feasibility of using PWAs and iframes in iOS and Android applications, user behavior, product scope, and the architecture and implementation of a project. They discuss AI coaching, meeting facilitation, the role of experts, the best use of Jonas's time for the Workshop Builder project, and the importance of asking powerful questions in coaching sessions.

Jonas and Cuan also address the purpose and functionality of the subvisor, the scope and hierarchy of workshops, technical challenges and solutions for running workshops, and various forms and contexts of workshops. They interact during discussions, providing examples and insights, with Cuan often guiding Jonas through the workshop process. They discuss the system's cost, scalability, architectural direction, the need for impactful demonstrations, and the review system.

Their collaboration includes debugging and fixing issues, defining and implementing segments, goal setting, prompting techniques, planning and scheduling tasks, resolving issues related to the bot's functionality, and prompt engineering. They work on the development and functionality of a calorie tracking system and other related applications, the review and segment systems, bandwidth issues, project planning, and the refinement of advanced steps and testing capabilities</data>

      <data key=d5>Jorge Lewis and Cuan Mulligan are both actively involved in a wide range of discussions and collaborative efforts related to various projects and technical developments. They are participants in meetings and conversations that cover topics such as the chat interface, application functionalities, project alignment, technical details, user interface, bot instructions, and technical issues. Their discussions also extend to innovative ideas, business strategies, message completion, product development, streaks, milestones, the review system, the role of supervisors and agents, and the coding and development plan for Adapta.

Both Jorge and Cuan are deeply engaged in the development and improvement of bot systems, including the categorization of bot messages, daily check-ins, and the coaching application. They are also involved in discussions about the implementation and functionality of systems for generating prompts and responses, data quality, and coaching. Their collaboration includes defining concepts for user engagement, such as streaks, milestones, and badges, as well as tracking and visualizing user data quality and consistency.

In addition to technical discussions, Jorge and Cuan are involved in planning and executing projects, coordinating meeting schedules, and discussing project details, timelines, and progress. They address technical issues, potential solutions, and the practical bounds and cost optimization of systems. Their conversations also cover market conditions, strategic partnerships, hiring practices, and the iterative development of workshops.

Jorge and Cuan's collaboration extends to the development of gamification systems, including criteria and format for milestones and streaks, as well as the functionality and direction of user responses. They discuss the reuse of components between ADAPT and IntelliAgent, the differences between POC and MVP, and the trade-offs between rapid development and long-term architectural stability.

Their interactions include discussing the progress and challenges of the multi-agent system project, the role of bots in analyzing content and facilitating workshops, and the transition from POC to MVP. They also engage in conversations about creative processes, ideation, market conditions, strategic partnerships, and hiring practices.

Overall, Jorge Lewis and Cuan Mulligan are key participants in a variety of discussions and collaborative efforts, contributing their insights and expertise to the development and improvement of multiple projects and systems.</data>

      <data key=d5>Jonathan Phillips and Jorge Lewis are actively collaborating on various aspects of the IntelliAgent project. Jonathan and Jorge frequently interact, providing examples and insights, and coordinating on project management, updating contracts, and payment and technical progress. They discuss project timelines, the need for regular updates, and the current status of investments. Their conversations also include ethical considerations in content reproduction, improving prompt structure and effectiveness, and the review system.

They are engaged in discussions about the implementation and evolution of the Proof of Concept (POC) and Minimum Viable Product (MVP), market targeting, and strategies. They address the modifiability of check-in cycle points, the modularity and integration of components, and the role of the subvisor in multi-agent conversations. Jonathan and Jorge are both speakers in discussions about the goals and processes of a marketing agency and are involved in the project's core direction and response time issues.

Overall, Jonathan Phillips and Jorge Lewis are integral to the IntelliAgent project, contributing their expertise and insights across a broad spectrum of topics to drive the project's success.</data>
